<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is the best intermittent fasting schedule for beginners?", answer: "The 14:10 method (14 hours fasting, 10 hours eating) is the easiest starting point for beginners because it closely resembles a normal eating pattern — you simply skip late-night snacking. Once comfortable, most people progress to the 16:8 method (16 hours fasting, 8 hours eating), which is the most popular and well-studied IF protocol. Start with the easiest method and gradually extend your fasting window." },
  { question: "What can I eat or drink during the fasting window?", answer: "During the fasting window, you should consume zero-calorie beverages only: water, black coffee (no cream or sugar), plain tea, and sparkling water. Any food or caloric beverage will break your fast. Some people allow small amounts of apple cider vinegar or lemon water, as these contain minimal calories. Avoid artificial sweeteners during fasting as they may trigger an insulin response in some individuals." },
  { question: "How does the 16:8 intermittent fasting method work?", answer: "The 16:8 method involves fasting for 16 consecutive hours and eating all meals within an 8-hour window. For example, if you start fasting at 8 PM, you would not eat again until 12 PM the next day, then eat between 12 PM and 8 PM. Most people skip breakfast and eat lunch and dinner within the window. This method is sustainable long-term and has strong research support for weight management and metabolic health." },
  { question: "Will intermittent fasting cause muscle loss?", answer: "Intermittent fasting does not inherently cause muscle loss as long as you consume adequate protein (1.6-2.2 grams per kg of body weight per day) and continue resistance training. Research shows that IF preserves lean mass comparably to traditional dieting when protein intake and exercise are maintained. Some studies even suggest IF may enhance growth hormone production, which supports muscle preservation." },
  { question: "What is OMAD and is it safe?", answer: "OMAD (One Meal A Day) is an extreme form of intermittent fasting where you eat all daily calories in a single meal within approximately one hour. While some people thrive on OMAD, it can be difficult to consume adequate nutrition in one sitting. It is generally safe for healthy adults but is not recommended for beginners, pregnant women, people with eating disorders, or those with blood sugar regulation issues. Consult a healthcare provider before starting OMAD." }
]) %>

