    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Intermittent Fasting Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        This intermittent fasting calculator creates a personalized daily schedule based on your chosen fasting protocol and preferred start time. Select one of five popular fasting methods — 16:8, 18:6, 20:4, 14:10, or OMAD — then set the time you want to begin your fast (typically after your last meal in the evening). The calculator instantly generates your fasting and eating windows with exact times, plus a detailed daily schedule showing when to start and break your fast, mid-fast check-ins, and meal timing reminders.
      </p>
      <p>
        Intermittent fasting is one of the most popular dietary approaches for weight management, metabolic health, and longevity. By restricting when you eat rather than what you eat, IF simplifies meal planning and can naturally reduce calorie intake. Research supports benefits including improved insulin sensitivity, increased fat oxidation, enhanced cellular repair through autophagy, and reduced inflammation markers.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Popular Intermittent Fasting Methods</h2>
      <p>
        The <strong>16:8 method</strong> (Leangains protocol) is the most popular approach, involving 16 hours of fasting and an 8-hour eating window. Most people achieve this by skipping breakfast and eating between noon and 8 PM. The <strong>18:6 method</strong> extends the fast by two hours and is suitable for those who have adapted to 16:8. The <strong>20:4 method</strong> (Warrior Diet) restricts eating to a 4-hour window, typically one large meal and one small meal or snack. The <strong>14:10 method</strong> is the gentlest approach, ideal for beginners. <strong>OMAD</strong> (One Meal a Day) is the most restrictive daily protocol with a 23-hour fast and 1-hour eating window.
      </p>

      <h3>Tips for Successful Intermittent Fasting</h3>
      <p>
        Stay well hydrated during fasting hours with water, black coffee, or plain tea. Start with a shorter fast and gradually extend it. Break your fast with a balanced meal rich in protein, healthy fats, and vegetables rather than processed foods. Keep your eating window consistent from day to day to establish a routine your body can adapt to. Listen to your body — if you feel unwell, it is better to eat than to push through severe discomfort. Exercise can be done during either the fasting or eating window based on personal preference and performance.
      </p>

      <h3>Who Should Avoid Intermittent Fasting</h3>
      <p>
        Intermittent fasting is not appropriate for everyone. Pregnant or breastfeeding women, children and adolescents, people with a history of eating disorders, individuals with type 1 diabetes, and those taking medications that must be taken with food should avoid IF or consult their healthcare provider first. If you have any chronic health condition, it is important to discuss IF with your doctor before starting.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>What is the best intermittent fasting schedule for beginners?</h3>
      <p>
        The 14:10 method is the easiest starting point because it closely resembles a normal eating pattern. Once comfortable, most people progress to 16:8, which is the most popular and well-studied IF protocol.
      </p>

      <h3>What can I eat or drink during the fasting window?</h3>
      <p>
        During the fasting window, consume only zero-calorie beverages: water, black coffee, plain tea, and sparkling water. Any food or caloric beverage will break your fast.
      </p>

      <h3>How does the 16:8 intermittent fasting method work?</h3>
      <p>
        The 16:8 method involves fasting for 16 consecutive hours and eating all meals within an 8-hour window. Most people skip breakfast and eat lunch and dinner within the window.
      </p>

      <h3>Will intermittent fasting cause muscle loss?</h3>
      <p>
        IF does not inherently cause muscle loss as long as you consume adequate protein and continue resistance training. Research shows IF preserves lean mass comparably to traditional dieting when protein intake and exercise are maintained.
      </p>

      <h3>What is OMAD and is it safe?</h3>
      <p>
        OMAD is an extreme form of IF where you eat all daily calories in one meal within about one hour. It is generally safe for healthy adults but not recommended for beginners or those with blood sugar regulation issues.
      </p>

